%T A396085 29927,1,1,618,249926,28,110,1,2316317,4036,6,1,23674841,1,617,30035,
%U A396085 264329177,1,2,23,3207278255,249927,4035,1,42011308653,622,23
%N A396085 Number of fixed-content bracelets of length n, summed over all integer partitions of n, whose mirror image is a rotation of the original word, with exactly one palindromic rotation and a nontrivial rotational symmetry.
%C A396085 A necklace is a circular word considered up to rotation. A bracelet is a necklace considered up to rotation and reversal. For an integer partition lambda = (lambda_1, ..., lambda_k) of n, use k colors and require color i to occur lambda_i times. Thus lambda records the multiplicities of the colors, not the colors themselves; relabeling the colors does not give a new contribution for the same partition lambda.
%C A396085 This sequence counts only those fixed-content bracelets represented by a circular word X such that (1) the mirror image of X is a rotation of X, (2) X has exactly one palindromic rotation, and (3) some non-identity rotation fixes X. Equivalently, these are the symmetric fixed-content bracelets of palindrome class S1 with a nontrivial cyclic stabilizer.
%C A396085 Every counted word is a power X = U^(n/d), where the rotational period d is a proper divisor of n and U is a word of length d whose cyclic orbit is closed under reversal, has full period d, and has exactly one palindromic rotation; the correspondence U -> U^(n/d) preserves all three defining conditions, since a power W^j is a palindrome if and only if W is. Such U exist only for odd d, and for odd d they are counted by the aperiodic-palindrome formula below. Hence a(n) depends only on the odd proper divisors of n; in particular a(p) = 1 for every prime p, coming from the single-color word.
%C A396085 This sequence refines the partition-indexed bracelet count A213943 by splitting according to mirror-image behavior, palindromic rotations, and rotational symmetry. The related cases give disjoint subcounts of A213943(n).
%C A396085 Can be computed either from the divisor formula below or by enumerating fixed-content necklaces with Sawada's algorithm and then classifying each necklace by mirror-image behavior, palindromic rotations, and rotational period.
%H A396085 Andrea Cutri, <a href="/A396085/b396085.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..400</a>
%F A396085 a(n) = Sum_{d | n, d < n, d odd} g(d), where g(d) = Sum_{e | d} mu(d/e) * T(e) is the number of aperiodic linear palindromes of odd length d with partition-indexed content, T(m) = Sum_{lambda partition of m with exactly one odd part} ((m-1)/2)! / Product_i floor(lambda_i/2)!, and mu is the Moebius function.
%F A396085 a(n) = 1 + Sum_{d | n, d < n, d odd, d >= 3} A395436((d-1)/2).
%F A396085 a(p) = 1 for p prime.
%e A396085 For n=6 the odd proper divisors are 1 and 3, each contributing one bracelet. The divisor d=1 gives the single-color word 000000 (partition [6]). The divisor d=3 gives 001001, the square of the aperiodic word 001 (partition [4,2]): its mirror image 100100 is a rotation of 001001; among its three distinct rotations 001001, 010010, 100100 exactly one, namely 010010, is a palindrome; and rotation by 3 places fixes the word. Circular words obtained only by permuting the color names are not additional objects for the same partition. Hence a(6) = 2.
%Y A396085 Cf. A005651, A072605, A213943, A395436, A396630, A396631, A396632.
